\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Determinants of the Gender Gap in Productivity and Gross Revenue from Maize in Eastern Uganda
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Emma Prati
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This study investigates gender differences in maize productivity and maize revenue in Eastern Uganda,
 with a focus on the impact of improved seed adoption.
 Using a mixed-methods approach,
 the analysis combines quantitative and qualitative data with a focus on male and female headed households in the Busoga region.
 First,
 ordinary least squares models are estimated to descriptively examine gender gaps across productivity and income from maize.
 Both baseline and pooled panel data covering three rounds of data collection are used.
 Following that,
 a threefold Oaxaca-Blinder decomposition technique is employed at baseline to decompose gender gaps in productivity and income from maize into differences in endowments and differences in returns to those endowments.
 Qualitative analysis and focus group discussions complement econometric analysis by giving contextual information about gendered dynamics in maize production in the Busoga region.
 The findings show that female-headed households have lower maize productivity and substantially lower maize revenue than male-headed households.
 The decomposition results suggest that these gaps are only partly explained by differences in observable characteristics,
 while unequal returns to these resources and broader structural constraints remain key components of the gap.
 Qualitatively,
 we found that these gaps are shaped by unequal labour division,
 time constraints,
 and gendered control over maize-related resources.
 Women’s agricultural work is often combined with domestic and care responsibilities,
 limiting their time and productive capacity.
 Unequal control over maize revenue,
 social expectations,
 and discriminatory market dynamics further constrain women’s ability to benefit from maize production.
\end_layout

