\begin_layout Standard
The paper contributes to the bulk of evidence on gender differentials in agricultural maize productivity and gross revenue by analyzing household-level panel data from 3,500 smallholder maize farmers from the Busoga region,
 in Eastern Uganda.
 I estimate baseline and pooled OLS models and apply Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition to assess the relative contribution of differences in endowments versus structural differences in returns to these endowments in determining productivity and gross revenue gaps from maize.
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Furthermore,
 the analysis quantifies the impact of adoption of improved maize seed varieties on productivity and income gaps between female and male headeded households.
 To address the potential endogeneity of adoption decisions,
 an instrumental variables (IV) strategy was used to estimate the causal impact of adopting improved seed on maize productivity and income for female-headed households and male-headed households.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In parallel,
 we conducted a qualitative analysis consisting of 16 focus group discussions with smallholder farmers in the same region.
 This mixed-methods approach provide a comprehensive understanding of gendered constraints in agricultural production.
 By jointly examining the descriptive outcomes,
 the causal components,
 and the qualitative data,
 the paper provides policy relevant evidence on the mechanisms through which gender gaps in smallholder maize systems persist.
 Understanding these gender differentiated constraints is essential for achieving an inclusive agricultural transformation,
 improving welfare and food security.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results show that female-headed households achieve significantly lower maize productivity and revenue than male-headed households,
 and that these gaps persist even after accounting for observable differences in household and plot characteristics.
 The Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition indicates that unequal returns to resources,
 rather than unequal access to them,
 account for the majority of both gaps,
 roughly three-quarters of the productivity gap and more than half of the revenue gap.
 The qualitative evidence points to unequal labour division,
 time constraints,
 and gendered market discrimination as key mechanisms underlying these structural disparities.
\end_layout

