\begin_layout Section
Theoretical Framework and Hypotesis 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:2-Theoretical-Framework and Hypotesis-1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
shall I mention that my hypotesis change also through the qualitative fieldwork and maybe:
 The literature reviewed above suggests that gender gaps in smallholder agriculture arise from two broad sources:
 unequal access to productive resources,
 or endowments (land,
 inputs,
 credit,
 education,
 labour),
 and unequal returns to those same resources,
 driven by structural and institutional constraints such as discriminatory social norms,
 unequal decision-making power,
 and imperfect markets (Fortin,
 Lemieux,
 & Firpo,
 2011).
 The Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition formalizes this distinction by separating an observed gender gap into an explained (endowment) component and an unexplained (structural/coefficient) component,
 and has been the standard tool for studying gender gaps in agricultural productivity since Kilic,
 Palacios-López,
 and Goldstein (2015) first applied it in this setting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This study investigates gender gaps between male-headed and female-headed household rather than between male- and female-managed plots within the same household.
 As De la O Campos et al.
 (2016) show,
 the choice of gender indicator materially affects both the magnitude of the estimated gap and its interpretation:
 intra-household approaches capture bargaining and labour allocation within a household,
 while inter-household approaches capture how households headed by women are treated differently by markets and communities around them.
 Given that the data identify gender only at the household-head level,
 we adopt the inter-household framing throughout.
 why do I take it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I first examine the gender gap in maize productivity.
 Evidence on whether endowment or structural effects dominate this gap is mixed across contexts:
 studies from Malawi and Tanzania find that the productivity gap is mostly explained by unequal access to inputs (endowment effects),
 whereas studies from Ethiopia and southwest Nigeria find that most of the gap remains unexplained after controlling for observable characteristics,
 pointing to structural constraints.
 Notably,
 Bello,
 Baiyegunhi,
 Danso-Abbeam,
 and Ogundeji (2021),
 using an Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition on Nigerian rice farmers in female and male headed households,
 find that 77.7 percent of the productivity gap is structural rather than endowment-driven.
 I hypothesize that Uganda maize data will show a similar pattern because household headship is associated with differential treatment in labour markets,
 care activities,
 extension access,
 and community support networks,
 mechanisms that are not fully captured by observable covariates.
 Therefore,
 I expect the structural component to exceed the endowment component in the productivity decomposition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Subsequently,
 I turn to the gender gap in maize revenue,
 arguing that the revenue gap cannot be simply treated as a consequence of the productivity gap.
 First,
 revenue combines two distinct margins:
 the decision to participate in the maize market at all (the extensive margin),
 and,
 conditional on participating,
 the quantity sold and the price obtained (the intensive margin).
 Second,
 these two margins are governed by different mechanisms.
 Marenya,
 Kassie,
 Jaleta,
 and Rahut (2017),
 applying an Oaxaca–Blinder framework to maize market positions of MHH and FHH in Ethiopia,
 find that structural/coefficient effects mostly explain the gap in the probability of being a net seller (check if it's not net buyer).
 This asymmetry suggests that market access is shaped by structural constraints such as information asymmetries,
 exclusion,
 mobility,
 and negotiating power.
 This distinction is directly relevant to our data:
 48.8 percent of households in our baseline sample report zero maize revenue,
 and this share is substantially higher among FHH than among MHH,
 indicating that the extensive margin is itself an important source of the gender gap in revenue,
 separate from productivity.
 However,
 the analysis also hypothesizes that,
 once having decided to sell,
 also the revenue is shaped by structural constraints (this was confirmed by the qualitative fieldwork and FGD reported in section X).
 Market discrimination could constrain women headed households with price differentiation,
 also with the same productive resources.
 A similar decomposition of maize revenue in the South African cabbage sector (Mkuna & Wale,
 2023) likewise attributes a substantial share of the income gap to structural effects related to access to markets,
 credit,
 and land tenure security.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Understanding why male-headed and female-headed households achieve different outcomes in maize production requires distinguishing between two related but analytically separate sources of inequality:
 unequal access to productive resources,
 and unequal returns to those same resources once they are held.
 This distinction,
 formalized in the labour economics literature as the split between endowment and structural (or coefficient) effects,
 provides the backbone of the empirical strategy that follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The starting point is historical.
 Boserup (1970) shows that Sub-Saharan Africa has long been characterized by what she terms "female farming systems",
 in which women historically held direct control over agricultural production,
 decision-making,
 and surplus,
 in contrast to the "male farming systems" typical of much of Asia.
 Colonial administrations and subsequent modernization efforts,
 however,
 systematically redirected credit,
 extension services,
 improved inputs,
 and formal land titles toward men,
 regardless of who was actually farming.
 This process did not simply fail to help women;
 it actively reallocated the institutional infrastructure of agriculture around male farmers.
 The implication for this study is that the endowment gap I expect to observe between MHH and FHH is not an incidental feature of the data,
 but the traceable legacy of a long-run institutional process that continues to shape access to inputs,
 credit,
 and formal recognition today.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This historical account,
 however,
 explains why resources came to be distributed unequally;
 it does not by itself explain why household headship,
 specifically,
 should be the relevant unit of analysis,
 rather than gender more broadly.
 For this,
 I draw on Whitehead's (1981) concept of the conjugal contract,
 developed from fieldwork with the Kusasi in Ghana.
 Whitehead shows that husbands and wives do not typically pool their labour and income into a single,
 jointly managed household economy;
 instead,
 they operate under an implicit and often unequal contract,
 with separate obligations,
 separate plots,
 and separate claims on income,
 mediated through the marital relationship itself.
 Kasente et al.
 (2002),
 applying this framework directly to non-traditional agricultural exports in Uganda,
 show that this negotiated structure continues to organize access to inputs and control over revenue in commercial farming.
 The relevance for this study is direct:
 a female-headed household is not simply a male-headed household with fewer resources.
 It is a household missing the entire negotiating counterpart,
 the person who,
 under normal circumstances,
 mediates with input dealers,
 extension officers,
 creditors,
 and buyers on the household's behalf.
 This is the theoretical basis for treating MHH and FHH as meaningfully different units,
 and for hypothesizing that a gap between them exists in the first place (H1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having established why a gap should exist,
 the framework turns to why part of that gap should persist even after accounting for observable endowments.
 Kabeer (1999) offers a useful starting point here,
 distinguishing between resources,
 agency,
 and achievements as three separate ingredients of empowerment.
 Her central argument is that possessing a resource is not the same as having the power to decide how it is used:
 a household may report using fertilizer,
 but the survey variable does not tell us who decided to apply it,
 when,
 or how carefully.
 This distinction matters directly for productivity,
 because it implies that equal input use recorded in the data does not guarantee equal outcomes.
 A concrete illustration is time allocated to care work:
 two plots may show identical input levels,
 yet if the person responsible for the plot is also solely responsible for childcare,
 cooking,
 and household maintenance,
 the timing and intensity of labour applied to the plot,
 weeding at the right moment,
 monitoring pest damage,
 will systematically differ,
 without this difference ever appearing in the input variables themselves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is precisely the mechanism that Tsikata (2009) develops further in the context of African agrarian and informal economies.
 Tsikata argues that women's agricultural labour is routinely rendered statistically invisible:
 care responsibilities are not simply an additional burden layered onto farm work,
 they compete directly with it for the same hours,
 and this competition is not captured by any of the standard productivity covariates.
 Because female household heads carry the full weight of domestic and care obligations without a co-resident partner to share or offset them,
 I expect this time constraint to bind more tightly for FHH than for MHH,
 producing a productivity gap that persists even when land,
 seed,
 and fertilizer use are held constant.
 Taken together,
 Kabeer and Tsikata provide the theoretical basis for expecting that the productivity gap between MHH and FHH will not be fully explained by differences in observable endowments,
 and that the structural,
 unexplained component,
 capturing precisely this kind of unmeasured time and agency constraint,
 will account for a larger share of the gap than endowments do (H2).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The final piece of the framework addresses revenue,
 which I treat as governed by a distinct mechanism from productivity:
 market discrimination.
 Two classic theories of discrimination,
 taken together,
 describe how this can generate a structural gap in revenue independently of any productivity difference.
 Becker (1957) describes taste-based discrimination,
 in which a buyer or institution holds an outright preference against transacting with a certain group,
 and is willing to forgo an otherwise profitable exchange to avoid it;
 this is consistent with the social stigma,
 at times amounting to accusations of witchcraft,
 directed at economically successful female-headed households in the qualitative fieldwork for this study.
 Arrow (1973) and Phelps (1972) describe statistical discrimination,
 in which a trader who cannot verify an individual seller's reliability or knowledge instead uses group membership,
 being a woman selling independently,
 as a proxy for risk or ignorance,
 resulting in worse prices,
 manipulated scales,
 or exclusion from credit.
 Whether the mechanism is outright prejudice or statistical inference under imperfect information,
 the outcome is the same:
 two households with identical maize output can receive systematically different revenue simply because of who is selling it and under what household structure.
 On this basis,
 I expect that the revenue gap,
 like the productivity gap,
 will persist after controlling for observable endowments such as plot size and input use,
 and that its structural component,
 reflecting these market-level discriminatory mechanisms rather than resource access,
 will exceed the endowment component (H3).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on this conceptual framework,
 the study tests the following hypotheses:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
H1:
 MHH and FHH differ in productivity and revenue from maize.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
H2:
 The gender gap in maize productivity between MHH and FHH persists after controlling for observable endowments,
 and the structural component of the gap exceeds the endowment component
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
H3:
 The gender gap in maize revenue between MHH and FHH persists after controlling for observable endowments,
 and the structural component of the gap exceeds the endowment component
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Literature Review
\lang english

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec3 -Literature Review"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper contributes to the literature on gender gaps in the agricultural sector (Duflo & Udry,
 2004,
 Peterman et al.,
 2010,
 Kilic et al.,
 2015;
 Palacios-López & Lopez,
 2015;
 Ali et al.,
 2016).
 Building on the intra-household approach,
 after estimating the gap through descriptive statistics and OLS regressions,
 we advance the literature that disentangles the roles of endowment versus structural effects in driving gender disparities.
 Women face two broad categories of constraints:
 first,
 limited access to assets and productive resources (an endowment gap),
 and second,
 discriminatory social norms and institutional practices that reduce the returns they can derive from those resources (a structural constraint).
 A common approach to analyzing such gaps is the Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition of mean differences,
 a well-established empirical strategy in labor economics,
 originally developed by Oaxaca (1973) and Blinder (1973).
 Kilic,
 Palacios-López,
 and Goldstein (2015) were the first to apply this approach to the analysis of agricultural productivity and a growing number of studies followed (Palacios-López and Lopez,
 2015;
 Slavchevska ,
 2015;
 Ali et al.,
 2016;
 and De la O Campos et al.,
 2016).
 Extending this framework,
 we employ the Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition to examine gender gaps in both agricultural productivity and gross income from maize production.
 The existing literature indicates that both endowments and structural mechanisms play a role in shaping the observed gaps in agricultural productivity and income (Buehren,
 2023).
 Numerous studies on the productivity gap demonstrate that the estimated gap significantly narrows once controlled for variations in access to productive inputs (Kinkingninhoun-Mêdagbé et al.,
 2010;
 Peterman et al.,
 2014;
 Kilic et al.,
 2015;
 De la O Campos et al.,
 2016),
 highlighting the key importance of access to inputs in observed yields differentials.
 For example,
 De la O Campos et al.
 (2016) demonstrate that the gender gap in agricultural productivity in Uganda diminishes once differences in access to production factors,
 such as fertilizers and pesticides,
 are taken into account.
 In this regard,
 also Kilic et al.
 (2015) suggest that disparities in asset ownership,
 such as machinery and new technology,
 substantially contribute to the gender gap in productivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 other studies find that productivity and income gaps persist even after equalizing for input access,
 identifying structural constraints,
 resource allocation,
 and returns to inputs as the main contributors (Kinkingninhoun-Medagb´e et al.,
 2010;
 Palacios-López ´ and Lopez ´,
 2015;
 Ali et al.,
 2016 ;
 Dandonougbo et al.
 2023).
 Literature shows that child dependency ratio,
 social expectation and time poverty play a key role in shaping these differences (Ali et al.,
 2016;
 Sell et al.,
 2018;
 Pierotti et al.,
 2022;
 Donald et al.,
 2023).
 According to Sell et al.
 (2018),
 women’s lower level of productivity is negatively associated with the number of household members.
 Time constraints may be more binding for women as a great proportion of their time is devoted to activities that do not generate an income,
 such as childcare,
 elderly care and food preparation and prevent them from engaging in agricultural activities (Buehren,
 2023 & Pierotti et al.,
 2022).
 In Uganda,
 for example,
 evidence shows that two fifths of the gender gap in productivity are explained by unequal returns to the child dependency ratio (Ali et al.,
 2016).
 Evidence from the literature also suggests that social norms and expectations in market orientation and risk preferences could explain the gender gap in productivity (Ali et al,
 2016;
 Duflo & Udry,
 2004;
 Reynolds et al.,
 2020).
 Women usually place lower value on cash crops,
 overlooking income potential and high market prices,
 while favoring food security (Duflo & Udry,
 2004).
 Other factors that might explain the gender gap in productivity and income from maize are the discriminations in labour and credit markets (Kilic et al.,
 2015;
 Palacios-López & Lopez,
 2015;
 Ali et al.,
 2016;).
 Palacios-López and Lopez (2015) claim that correcting market failures could positively impact female farmers’ productivity.
 Limited access to financial credit further constrains women’s ability to adopt modern technologies,
 machinery,
 and improved agricultural practices,
 reinforcing existing productivity and income disparities (Buehren,
 2023).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although these contributions provide a meaningful overview,
 context-specific analysis is required to effectively guide policy recommendations.
 We extend this body of work by estimating gender gaps in agricultural productivity and income from maize in male and female headed households using plot-level data from the Busoga region of Uganda for 2021–2022.
 Gender gap in agricultural productivity,
 particularly in maize production,
 usually translates into a gender gap in income,
 as documented by Buehren (2023),
 thereby reinforcing processes of feminiation of poverty.
 However,
 while gender disparities in agricultural productivity have been extensively studied,
 evidence on gendered income differentials from farming in Africa remains limited and fragmented (Mkuna & Wale,
 2023),
 especially in maize production in Uganda.
 Mkuna and Wale (2023) records gender income gap of approximately 50% in cabbage farmers in South Africa.
 Previous research suggests that the average agricultural farm income gap observed between men and women is about 66% in Togo rural areas (Dandonougbo et al.,
 2023).
 Through a study in Benin on rice production,
 Kinkingninhoun-Mêdagbé et al.
 (2010) show that the average income of men is more than four times that of women.
 These findings motivate further investigation into the income gap in maize production in Uganda.
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The literature shows that prevailing cultural norms and local systems of land access often disadvantage women,
 who rarely inherit land and instead cultivate plots borrowed from husbands or relatives,
 frequently consisting of smaller and lower-quality parcels;
 this pattern of gender-based marginalization in land allocation,
 both in terms of quantity and quality,
 has been widely documented in Sub-Saharan Africa (Basile,
 2001;
 Dey Abbas,
 1997;
 Saito et al.,
 1994;
 Palmer,
 1991;
 Lubbock,
 1988),
 suggesting that differences in endowments could play a key role in shaping different agricultural outcomes.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While decomposition methods identify the relative contribution of observable characteristics and structural differences,
 they do not establish causal relationships.
 After presenting descriptive evidence,
 the paper examines the causal relationship between the adoption of hybrid maize seeds varieties and both maize productivity and gross farm income using an instrumental variables (IV) approach.
 Existing research on gender inequalities in access to agricultural technologies has largely focused on inorganic fertilizers,
 while evidence on improved seed adoption remains vague (Peterman et al.,
 2010).
 Doss and Morris (2001) find that once controlled for complementary inputs,
 differences in adoption rates between male and female farmers largely disappear.
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
According to several studies,
 technology adoption represents one of the main channels through which differences in access to inputs translate into productivity and income disparities (source)
\end_layout

\end_inset

In contrast,
 other studies argue that even with similar access to modern inputs,
 women often obtain lower returns from their use (Tiruneh et al.,
 2001;
 Sanginga et al.,
 2007).
 Djurfeldt (2013) claims that the benefits of technology adoption depend not only on access to inputs but also on the ability to integrate into markets dynamics,
 highlighting the role of commercialization,
 access to markets and information.
 The weaknesses in agricultural credit markets further limit farmers’ ability to finance investments in improved inputs (Sheahan & Barrett,
 2017).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper contributes to this literature by extending the analysis of gender gaps beyond productivity alone and jointly examining adoption of improved seed varieties,
 productivity,
 and gross income outcomes.
 By combining causal estimation with decomposition methods and qualitative evidence,
 the study provides new evidence on the mechanisms through which gender disparities in smallholder maize systems arise and persist.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Data and Context
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Data-and-Context"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ugandan Context
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maize is cultivated by the majority of rural households in East Africa,
 making the Ugandan experience broadly comparable to that of other African countries (Sell et al.,
 2018).
 Previous research suggests that climate change is expected to have a significant negative effect on maize production in Uganda,
 with projected yield losses of around 5% by 2050 (Kikoyo & Norbert,
 2016).
 mention employment of population and percentage of gdp in agriculture.
 In an agricultural context with such constraints and challenges,
 where increasing yields through cultivated area is not possible,
 understanding underlying causes behind low agricultural performance becomes essential for food security.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quantitative Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Quantitative Sample
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The paper uses panel data from three survey rounds with approximately 3,500 smallholder maize farmers in southeastern Uganda.
 The data were originally collected within a broader research project examining agro-input dealers and farmer interactions in Uganda (De et al.,
 2024;
 Miehe et al.,
 2025,
 2026).
 The agro-dealer sample was constructed by listing all agro-dealers operating across eleven districts in the Busoga region,
 an area characterized by smallholder maize production,
 where maize serves both as a staple food and a cash crop.
 To link agro-dealers with farmers,
 each agro-dealer was asked to identify the villages where most of their customers reside.
 Enumerators then randomly sampled ten maize-growing households from each of these villages,
 yielding the sample of 3,470 farmers.
 This sampling frame allows us to assume that sampled farmers have reasonable access to improved maize varieties,
 should they choose to adopt them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Enumerators interviewed the household member most knowledgeable about maize cultivation.
 A subset of questions specifically targeted the household head,
 who may or may not have been the respondent.
 In addition to general information on agricultural practices,
 farmers were asked to list all their maize plots,
 from which one was randomly selected for detailed data collection.
 This approach minimized survey duration and respondent burden while preserving representativeness at the household level,
 due to the random selection of plots.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first round of data were collected in April 2021,
 followed by the second round of surveys in January-February 2022 and third round of surveys in July-August 2022.
 Of the 3,470 farmers interviewed in the first round of data collection,
 3,407 were re-interviewed at second one and 3,441 at the third round.
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In our case,
 plot-level measures of soil quality and others are missing.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Measurement of Key Outcome Variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analysis focuses on three main outcome variables:
 agricultural productivity,
 income from maize and the adoption of improved maize seeds varieties.
 All variables are measured on the randomly selected plot.
 Agricultural productivity is measured as maize yield per unit of cultivated land,
 capturing differences in output across plots.
 Maize gross revenue is measured as the gross value of maize sales,
 expressed in Ugandan shillings.
 For households that did not sell maize,
 income is set to zero.
 For households that reported selling maize,
 income is calculated as the quantity sold multiplied by the unit price received.
 Observations with missing information on sold quantities or bag prices among sellers are left as missing.
 The estimated decomposition reflects differences in both market participation and conditional revenue,
 as zero income observations represent non-participation in maize sales.
 Hybrid seeds adoption is measured as a binary indicator equal to one if the household reports using one of the officially recognized hybrid maize varieties (Longe 10H,
 Longe 7H,
 Longe 7R Kayongo-go,
 Bazooka,
 Longe 6H,
 Panner,
 Wema,
 or KH series) on the randomly selected plot during the reference season,
 and zero otherwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the skewed distribution and the presence of zero values in the outcome variables,
 maize productivity and gross income are transformed using the inverse hyperbolic sine (IHS) transformation in the empirical analysis.
 Skewness is according to the adjusted Fisher-Pearson coefficient of skewness exceeding 1.96.
 To address the recent critiques by Mullahy and Norton (2022) we applied the IHS transformation cautiously when dealing with outcome variables that have many zeros and impacts on the extensive margin.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The descriptive statistics,
 reported in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "descriptive statistics"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 report significant differences in maize productivity,
 income from maize sales and hybrid seeds adoption between male and female headed households.
 Productivity is higher for male-headed households,
 both in standard units (kg/acre) and when using the IHS transformation.
 Similarly,
 income from maize sales shows a statistically significant difference in levels and IHS terms,
 favoring male-headed households.
 
\end_layout

