\begin_layout Subsubsection
Quantitative Data Limitations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The assessment of gender gaps in agriculture generally relies on two different empirical approaches and indicators that significantly influence the analysis of gender differences (De la O Campos et al.,
 2016).
 This paper makes use of inter-household analyses,
 which compare agricultural production in male and female headed households.
 The alternative approach adopts an intra-household perspective,
 comparing production on female and male managed plots within the same household,
 allowing household characteristics to be held constant.
 As mentioned by Ali et al.
 (2016),
 since most female-managed plots are located within male-headed households,
 the first approach may draw inferences from a non-representative subset of women farmers and misclassify plots by gender.
 The use of household headship is further problematic because it does not capture who makes agricultural decisions or controls productive assets,
 nor does it account for intra-household power dynamics that shape resource allocation (Udry,
 1996).
 Despite that,
 the intra-household approach requires more detailed data and may face limitations in sample size and external validity.
 In this study,
 the use of an inter-household approach is driven by data availability,
 as gender information was collected at the level of the household head,
 making intra-household quantitative analysis infeasible.
 Nevertheless,
 this limitation is partly addressed through qualitative data,
 which provide insights into intra-household decision-making processes and power relations and complement the inter-household quantitative analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The paper can rely on relatively few female-headed households,
 which limits statistical power of the analysis.
 At baseline,
 we recorded the gender of the household head,
 identifying 774 female-headed households (22% of 3,470 farmers).
 At the endline,
 we recorded 760 female household heads (23% of 3,299).
 No information on the gender of the household head was collected at the midline stage;
 however,
 it is unlikely that there were any substantial changes during this period.
 Therefore,
 for the midline analysis,
 the gender classification observed at baseline and endline was assumed to remain unchanged.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These limitations represent a weakness of the study.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Qualitative Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Qualitative Sample
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The qualitative component of the data is based on fieldwork conducted in the Busoga region in south-east Uganda.
 Taking place over approximately 15 days between November and December 2025,
 the fieldwork covered several villages in the districts of Iganga,
 Bugweri,
 Bugiri and Mayuge.
 Sixteen focus group discussions (FGDs) were held,
 each with 10 participants (160 participants in total).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The composition of the groups was defined to capture specific gender perspectives,
 therefore 5 FGDs were women-only,
 5 were men-only,
 and 6 were mixed.
 The single-gender groups were used to encourage the participants to freely express experiences and opinions by reducing possible effects of bias and power asymmetries that can arise in mixed contexts.
 On the other hand,
 mixed groups allowed us to observe how intra-family norms and roles are reproduced in the discussion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Participants were selected randomly,
 ensuring a range of ages,
 with all participants being adults.
 All the people selected were plot managers,
 but not necessarily the household head.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Qualitative Content and Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The discussions were guided by a semi-structured outline consisting mainly of open-ended questions,
 probes and follow-ups.
 Moreover,
 to stimulate an open and participatory discussion,
 participants were encouraged to reflect on concrete examples and real-life situations.
 The questions (provided in the Appendix) covered topics related to gender norms,
 the division of labour and time use,
 economic empowerment,
 decision-making processes,
 power dynamics within the households,
 the adoption of new technology,
 and market access.
 All FGDs were conducted in Lusoga language by two enumerators and lasted an average of about two hours.
 In all of them it was ensured privacy and confidentiality.
 In particular,
 women and male partners were not involved in the same session as this could compromise safety or freedom of expression.
 The qualitative work aimed to contextualize the quantitative results and explore underlying social mechanisms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Qualitative Data Limitations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
FGDs were conducted in Lusoga and later translated.
 Therefore,
 nuances,
 humor,
 and culturally embedded meanings can be lost or reshaped through translation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The enumerator's male gender may have limited openness in women-only groups,
 particularly on themes like home conflict,
 threats,
 and sexual duties.
 The occasional presence of local leaders (e.g.,
 chairperson) can further influence answers toward "community-approved" narratives and diminish participants' willingness to criticize norms.
 Although qualitative findings help explain reasons why disparities may persist,
 there is no direct correlation between specific FGD participants and survey households.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover,
 the qualitative findings are highly context-specific,
 including gender norms,
 labor arrangements,
 and market interactions unique to the Busoga region in Eastern Uganda.
 Nevertheless,
 the revealed mechanisms may help us to understand gender-based restrictions in similar rural settings,
 assuming that contextual differences are carefully recognised.
 
\end_layout

