\end_layout

\end_inset

 Using the LPM,
 in Section 5 coefficients are interpreted as percentage-point changes in the probability of adoption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In equation (1),
 β measures the conditional effect of X on the outcome (or,
 in the case of adoption,
 in the probability of adoption) between male and female headed households.
 Gh is a binary indicator equal to one if the household head is male and zero otherwise.
 The vector X includes a set of control variables commonly used in the literature on gender gaps in agricultural outcomes (Kinkingninhoun-Mêdagbé et al.,
 2010;
 Peterman et al.
 2010;
 Palacios-López & López,
 2015;
 Wayagi et al.,
 2025).
 The controls are household socio-economic characteristics,
 farm size and input use,
 labor availability,
 and access to markets and agricultural services.
 Due to data limitations,
 the analysis does not include detailed agro-climatic and soil quality indicators,
 such as rainfall variability or irrigation intensity,
 which may also affect agricultural outcomes.
 The error term εh captures unobserved factors affecting agricultural outcomes.
 The full set of covariates and the corresponding regression specifications are reported in Tables 2 and 3 in the results section.
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Some variables reported in the descriptive statistics are excluded from the regression analysis either because they are highly collinear with included covariates or because they could create problems of endogeneity.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to cross-section specifications based solely on the baseline sample,
 pooled ordinary least squares (OLS) regressions are estimated by combining baseline,
 midline and endline observations into a single household-level panel dataset.
 Using pooled sample increases the statistical power of the analysis and allows us to verify whether gender differences in agricultural outcomes persist over time once the observable characteristics of households and agricultural activity have been controlled for.
 In the pooled specification,
 the model takes the form:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y_{ht}=\alpha+\beta X_{ij}+\gamma G_{h}+\delta_{t}+\varepsilon_{ij}\label{eq:one-1-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 𝑡 denotes the survey round and 𝛿𝑡 represents survey-round fixed effects that capture time-specific factors affecting all households simultaneously,
 such as seasonal conditions,
 price fluctuations,
 or other aggregate shocks.
 Including fixed round effects enables comparisons to be made between male and female households within the same period,
 preventing average differences between rounds from being mistakenly attributed to gender.
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Fixed effects at the household level are not included in the analysis as these effects would absorb all the characteristics of the household that remain unchanged over time,
 including the gender variable (see Ali et al.,
 2016).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some of the covariates collected at baseline were not re-measured in the midline and endline surveys.
 These variables capture household characteristics,
 which we assume remain constant over the study period.
 Accordingly,
 baseline values are carried forward in the pooled panel analysis.
 These include education level,
 household size,
 age of the household head,
 distance to the nearest agro-input shop,
 and the number of agro-input shops in the village.
 As stated before,
 no information on the gender of the household head was collected at the midline stage;
 however,
 it is unlikely that there were any substantial changes during this period.
 Therefore,
 for the midline analysis,
 the gender classification observed at baseline and endline was assumed to remain unchanged.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All OLS specifications use robust standard errors.
 In pooled specifications,
 standard errors are clustered at the household level to account for repeated observations of the same household over time.
 Additional diagnostic checks,
 including tests for heteroskedasticity,
 functional-form sensitivity,
 multicollinearity,
 and influential observations,
 are used to assess the robustness of the estimates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Oaxaca-Blinder Decomposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To investigate the sources of gender disparities in productivity and income,
 we apply the Blinder-Oaxaca decomposition (Blinder,
 1973;
 Oaxaca,
 1973).
 The OLS regressions described provide the basis for the decomposition methods.
 This technique decomposes observed gender gaps into two components:
 the endowment effect and the structural effect.
 The endowment effect captures differences due to observable characteristics,
 such as access to land,
 credit,
 education,
 and inputs.
 The structural effect accounts for differences in returns to those resources,
 potentially reflecting discriminatory social norms or practices.
 The Oaxaca–Blinder decomposition therefore quantifies the contribution of observable characteristics commonly available in household survey data while acknowledging that unobserved data not computed in the equation,
 such as agro-ecological conditions may remain captured in the returns component (Fortin et al.,
 2011).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on the work of Kilic et al.
 (2015),
 we derived the average gap between men and women "D",
 expressed as the average difference in productivity and income:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D=E(Y_{m})-E(Y_{f})\label{eq:one-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{f}$
\end_inset

 denote the expected outcomes for male and female headed households,
 obtained from linear estimation of agricultural productivity and income expressed in inverse hyperbolic sine (IHS) units.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
