\begin_inset Formula $X_{f}$
\end_inset

 are vectors of observable household and farm characteristics for male and female headed households,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{𝛽}_{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{𝛽}_{f}$
\end_inset

 represent the associated vectors of coefficients for male and female headed households,
 respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By substituting expressions 5 and 6 into the definition of D,
 the overall gender gap can be expressed as a function of disparities in observable characteristics as well as differences in the returns to those characteristics:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D=(\bar{X}_{m}-\bar{X}_{f})\beta^{*}+\left[\bar{X}_{m}(\hat{\beta}_{m}-\hat{\beta}^{*})+\bar{X}_{f}(\hat{\beta}^{*}-\hat{\beta}_{f})\right]\label{eq:one-1-1-3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first term,
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\bar{X}_{m}-\bar{X}_{f})\beta^{*}$
\end_inset

is the explained component,
 or endowment effect.
 It captures the part of the gender gap attributable to differences in observable characteristics.
 The second term,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\bar{X}_{m}(\hat{\beta}_{m}-\hat{\beta}^{*})+\bar{X}_{f}(\hat{\beta}^{*}-\hat{\beta}_{f})\right]$
\end_inset

represents the structural or coefficient component and it captures the part of gap associated with differences in returns and coefficient structures between male and female headed households.
 Not only it captures potential structural constraints but also the influence of unobserved heterogeneity,
 measurement error,
 and omitted variables,
 such as land quality or agro-ecological conditions.
 Therefore,
 the structural component should be interpreted with caution as reflecting differential returns rather than direct evidence of discrimination (Fortin et al.,
 2011).
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
previously said
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 7 represent a classic OB twofold decomposition,
 while the threefold OB decomposition can be obtained by further separating the coefficient component into male and female sub-components.
 The male and female coefficient components measure how the coefficient structures differ/deviate from a pooled benchmark 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 To construct the benchmark as a counterfactual non-discriminatory structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 we use the coefficients from a pooled regression estimated on the combined sample of male- and female-headed households (Jann,
 2008).
 This approach,
 commonly adopted in the agricultural gender gap literature,
 avoids privileging either group’s returns structure as the benchmark and instead relies on the average returns observed in the overall production environment,
 under the assumption that male and female farmers operate within a similar agricultural system and production function.
 As a robustness check decompositions with male structure and female structure as benchmark are reported in the Appendix.
 
