\begin_layout Subsection
OLS Estimates of Gender Differences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tables 2,
 3,
 and 4 report OLS regression results on the determinants of maize productivity,
 maize income,
 and adoption of hybrid maize seeds varieties respectively,
 disaggregated by gender of the household head.
 For each outcome,
 Column (1) reports the raw gender gap estimated from a bivariate regression including only an indicator for male-headed households.
 Column (2) presents results from the full baseline specification controlling for household characteristics,
 access to input markets,
 and plot-level production factors.
 Columns (3) and (4) report gender-specific regressions estimated separately for male and female headed households,
 allowing returns to observable characteristics to differ by gender.
 Columns (5)–(7) present analogous pooled OLS regressions estimated on the combined sample of all survey rounds,
 including round fixed effects.
 Productivity and income from maize are expressed in inverse hyperbolic sine (IHS) units.
 We report household-clustered robust standard errors to account for heteroskedasticity and correlation of the error term within households across survey rounds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 2 presents regression results for maize productivity measured as yield per acre on the randomly selected plot.
 Column (1) shows a sizable and statistically significant raw gender gap:
 maize productivity on male-headed plots is approximately 20 percent higher than on female-headed plots.
 Importantly,
 this gap remains statistically significant and of similar magnitude after controlling for a comprehensive set of household- and plot-level characteristics (Column 2),
 indicating that observable endowments explain only a limited share of the productivity differential and pointing instead to differences in returns and unobserved constraints disproportionately affecting female farmers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several plot-level inputs are positively associated with maize productivity.
 Fertilizer use,
 particularly Urea,
 DAP/NPK application,
 and the use of organic manure,
 chemical inputs and quality seeds on the randomly selected plot are strongly correlated with higher yields,
 although the gender-differentiated regression reveal some heterogeneity in returns to these inputs.
 Education of the household head is positively associated with maize productivity among female-headed households,
 while the corresponding effect is small and statistically insignificant among male-headed households,
 suggesting that education may play a more important role in increasing productivity among female farmers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When pooling observations across survey rounds,
 the estimated gender coefficient remains positive and statistically significant,
 confirming that the productivity gap between male and female headed households persists over time,
 even after accounting for round-fixed effects.
 In particular,
 household size and the age of the household head become consistently and negatively associated with maize productivity,
 when considering the larger sample.
 The use of quality seeds and fertilizer inputs,
 including both DAP/NPK and urea,
 remains strongly and positively associated with productivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 3 reports analogous results for maize income derived from the randomly selected plot.
 The raw income gap in Column (1) is large and statistically significant,
 with male-headed households earning substantially higher maize income than female-headed households.
 Once controls are introduced (Column 2),
 the estimated gender gap declines but remains economically large and statistically significant,
 indicating that differences in plot size,
 input use,
 and household characteristics explain only part of the observed income disparity.
 Plot size,
 measured in logarithmic terms,
 emerges as a key determinant of maize income.
 Input use plays an important role in shaping income outcomes.
 The use of quality seeds,
 fertilizers,
 and chemical inputs is positively associated with maize income.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 gender-specific regressions reveal heterogeneity in returns across different inputs.
 While urea application is significantly associated with higher maize income among female-headed households,
 chemical inputs are significant only among male-headed households,
 suggesting that returns to specific inputs differ by gender rather than being uniformly higher for one group.
 As we have noticed with productivity,
 education of the household is positively associated with maize income among female-headed households,
 but not among male-headed households,
 indicating higher returns to human capital for female farmers.
 Household characteristics also matter.
 The household size and the age of the household head are negatively associated with income.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results from the pooled income specification indicate that the gender gap in maize income persists over time,
 with the estimated gender coefficient remaining positive and statistically significant.
 Plot size remains positively and statistically significant in the pooled specification,
 confirming that scale effects continue to play an important role in explaining differences in maize income across households over time.
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The pooled estimates reveal that time-varying production decisions play a more prominent role:
 the use of quality seeds,
 fertilizers and chemical inputs remains positively associated with maize income,
 with some coefficients increasing in magnitude relative to the baseline specification.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In both specifications,
 as expected,
 higher maize productivity is associated with higher income from maize,
 confirming the central role of agricultural performance in determining income.
 However,
 substantial gender disparities persist even after conditioning on productivity.
 This suggests that income gender disparities may be influenced by other factors beyond production.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 4 summarizes the factors influencing the adoption of improved maize seed varieties.
 In the raw specification (Column 1),
 male-headed households had a considerably higher likelihood of adoption.
 However,
 the effect disappears when household and plot-level characteristics are controlled for,
 suggesting that the gender differences in adoption are largely explained by unequal access to resources and inputs.
 These results are consistent with previous studies showing that once differences in access to inputs such as land,
 education and inputs are accounted for,
 gender itself does not significantly affect adoption of improved seeds (Doss,
 2001;
 Horrell & Krishnan,
 2007).
 The use of agricultural inputs,
 particularly DAP/NPK fertilizer,
 Urea,
 and chemicals,
 is positively and significantly associated with adoption both at baseline and in the pooled models,
 indicating that hybrid seeds are adopted as part of a broader input use.
 Education also increases the probability of adoption,
 with a stronger effect among female-headed households
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
,
 confirming the findings of Anang (2020)
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 There is also a significant association between membership in a farmer group or cooperative and adoption both for female and male headed households.
 Being part of a farmer organization increases the probability of using hybrid seeds,
 likely reflecting improved access to information,
 markets that reduce uncertainty surrounding new technologies.
 As stated in section 4,
 as a robustness check,
 we estimate logit models for hybrid seed adoption.
 The results,
 reported in the Appendix,
 are consistent with the linear probability model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although comparing raw and controlled specifications shows the extent to which observable factors contribute to the gender gap,
 this empirical technique does not identify the underlying mechanisms that drive differences between male and female headed households.
 The heterogeneous returns observed across the regressions motivate an explicit decomposition of productivity and income gaps,
 which we undertake in the following section using the Oaxaca–Blinder framework.
\end_layout

