\begin_layout Standard
Tables X and Y report the twofold and threefold Oaxaca–Blinder decompositions of the gender gaps in maize productivity and maize income.
 Both outcomes are expressed in inverse hyperbolic sine units and the estimated gaps can be interpreted approximately as percentage differences.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Since the gender gap is defined as the mean outcome of male-headed households minus that of female-headed households,
 positive values indicate higher average outcomes among male-headed households.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fixed-effects adjusted decomposition indicates a maize productivity gap of 0.197 IHS units,
 suggesting that on average female-headed households have about 20% lower maize productivity compared to male-headed households.
 This result is consistent with De la O Campos et al.
 (2016),
 who report a difference in mean log productivity between plots managed by male and female headed households of 0.177,
 corresponding to a gap of approximately 19.4%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The twofold decomposition shows that 0.051 IHS units,
 corresponding to 26.2 % of the productivity gap,
 are explained by observable differences in endowments.
 The remaining 0.145 IHS units,
 or 73.8 % of the gap is attributed to differences in returns to these characteristics,
 suggesting that gender disparities in maize productivity could be driven primarily by structural factors,
 differential returns to inputs,
 and gender-specific constraints (or with residual unobserved factors) rather than by unequal access to resources alone.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The threefold decomposition further separates the coefficient component into male and female coefficient components.
 For productivity,
 the endowment component is 0.051,
 the male coefficient component is 0.032,
 and the female coefficient component is 0.114.
 Both coefficient components contribute positively to the productivity gap,
 with the female coefficient component accounting for the larger share of the coefficient effect.
 This indicates that the productivity gap is not only associated with differences in observed characteristics,
 but also with the way these characteristics translate into productivity for female-headed households relative to the pooled benchmark.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As highlighted in the literature,
 aggregate decomposition results vary across crops and contexts,
 and the relative contribution of endowment and structural effects depends on how gender is conceptualized,
 whether in terms of household heads,
 plot holders,
 or farm managers (De la O Campos et al.,
 2016).
 Moreover,
 the allocation of the coefficient component into male and female coefficient components is sensitive to the choice of benchmark.
 For this reason,
 these components are interpreted descriptively as deviations from the pooled coefficient structure rather than as direct measures of male advantage or female disadvantage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The gender gap in maize income is substantially larger than the productivity gap.
 The estimated income gap of 0.975 corresponds to nearly 97% lower maize income among female-headed households relative to male-headed households.
 A sizable share of this gap (approximately 43%) is explained by differences in observable characteristics.
 Nevertheless,
 about 57% of the income gap is associated with differences in the coefficient structure.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
pointing to possible gender-based inequalities in market access and the ability to translate production into monetary returns
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Compared with productivity,
 observable endowments explain a larger share of the income gap,
 suggesting that differences in plot area,
 input use,
 and other household and farm characteristics play an important role in shaping income disparities.
 Nevertheless,
 more than half of the income gap remains associated with coefficient differences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The threefold income decomposition shows that the endowment component is 0.319,
 the male coefficient component is 0.093,
 and the female coefficient component is 0.331.
 As in the productivity decomposition,
 the female coefficient component represents the largest part of the coefficient effect.
 This pattern suggests that income disparities may be related not only to differences in productive resources,
 but also to gendered differences in the ability to convert those resources into monetary returns.
 However,
 due to the zero because maize income contains many zero observations,
 the income decomposition should be interpreted as reflecting both market participation and conditional earnings,
 rather than a single income generating process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The detailed decomposition provides additional insight into which specific covariates contribute the most to the explained and unexplained components of the gap.
 The detailed decomposition results are reported in the Appendix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the literature,
 despite focusing on male and female plot owners,
 Dandonougbo et al.
 (2023) find that 58.5% of the average farm income gap in Togo is accounted for by structural advantages enjoyed by male farmers.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The detailed decomposition provides additional insight into which specific covariates contribute the most to the explained and unexplained components of the gap.
 For maize productivity,
 the differences in education are among the most relevant contributor to the explained component.
 While primary education contributes positively to the explained component of the productivity gap,
 the differential returns appear to play a more substantial role,
 indicating unequal productivity returns from similar schooling levels.
 In the case of urea application,
 the negative structural contribution suggests that differences in returns to fertilizer do not amplify the productivity gap and may instead partially attenuate it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For maize income,
 the detailed results indicate that land size (log area) is a major contributor to the explained component,
 confirming that scale remains an important determinant of income disparities.
 In contrast,
 household size contributes negatively to the endowment component,
 indicating that differences in household composition partially offset the overall income gap.
 However,
 much of the income gap is driven by differences in returns across groups.
 Age,
 in particular,
 contributes substantially to this structural component,
 indicating that comparable age levels translate into different income outcomes for male and female headed households.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
These detailed results should be interpreted as descriptive accounting exercises.
 Given the maintained assumptions of additive linearity,
 overlapping support,
 and ignorability,
 the contribution of individual covariates reflects their role within the specified linear model and reference structure,
 rather than isolated structural parameters.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
5.2.1 Detailed Decomposition Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The detailed decompositions provide additional insight into which covariates contribute most to the explained and coefficient components of the gap.
 These detailed contributions are not causal effects of individual covariates;
 rather,
 they show how differences in observable characteristics and differences in estimated coefficient structures contribute mechanically to the overall gap.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For maize productivity,
 table x shows that 
\series bold
education
\series default
 contributes positively and significantly to the endowment component,
 indicating that differences in education levels widen the productivity gap.
 However,
 the coefficient component for education is negative,
 suggesting that differences in the education-productivity relationship reduce rather than widen the gap.
 Urea application shows a similar pattern:
 its endowment contribution is close to zero,
 while its coefficient component is negative and statistically significant.
 This suggests that differences in the coefficient structure associated with urea application reduce rather than amplify productivity disparities.
 Overall,
 through the detailed decomposition the productivity gap appears to reflect a combination of small endowment differences and differences in coefficient structures.
\end_layout

